# 📊 Virtual IR

**Virtual IR** is an interactive, browser-based infrared spectrum simulator for chemistry education. It allows users to compose IR spectra by combining functional groups and bonds, with real-time rendering and fine-grained signal control — all in a single self-contained HTML file, with no installation required.

---

## ✨ Features

- **Functional Group Library** — over 50 bonds and functional groups organized by chemical class (O-containing, N-containing, carbonyls, aromatics, alkenes, halogens, sulfur, phosphorus, etc.)
- **Combined & Separate View Modes** — visualize all active groups overlaid on a single spectrum, or display each group as an individual stacked trace
- **Per-group Controls**
  - Intensity slider (0–100%)
  - Individual peak shift per absorption band (±200 cm⁻¹)
  - Visibility toggle (show/hide without removing)
  - Color-coded identification
- **Signal Quality Controls**
  - Noise / S·N⁻¹ (0–8%)
  - Baseline slope adjustment
  - Peak width factor (0.4×–3.0×)
- **Display Options**
  - Custom chart title and Y-axis label
  - Peak wavenumber labels
  - Grid overlay
  - Peak annotation labels
- **IR Absorption Reference Table** — searchable modal with absorption ranges, intensities, and bond assignments for all included functional groups
- **Export**
  - PNG image (high-resolution canvas export)
  - CSV (Wavenumber vs. Transmittance data, semicolon-delimited)
- **Zero dependencies** — fully self-contained single HTML file; runs entirely in the browser

---

## 🚀 Getting Started

No installation or server required. Simply open the file in any modern browser:

```
double-click Virtual_IR.html
```

Or serve locally:

```bash
python3 -m http.server
# then open http://localhost:8000/Virtual_IR.html
```

---

## 🖥️ Interface Overview

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  VIRTUAL IR                         [ABSORPTION TABLE] [↓PNG] [↓CSV]  │
├───────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  LEFT SIDEBAR     │  CANVAS AREA                            │
│  ─────────────    │  ─────────────────────────────────────  │
│  Functional       │  [Combined] [Separate]   info bar       │
│  Groups / Bonds   │                                         │
│                   │  ┌─────────────────────────────────┐   │
│  Signal Quality   │  │                                 │   │
│                   │  │       IR Spectrum Canvas        │   │
│  Spectrum Display │  │      4000 → 500  cm⁻¹         │   │
│                   │  └─────────────────────────────────┘   │
│  [UPDATE]         │                                         │
└───────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Left Sidebar

| Section | Controls |
|---|---|
| **Functional Groups / Bonds** | Add, remove, toggle visibility, adjust intensity and per-peak shifts |
| **Signal Quality** | Noise level, baseline slope, peak width factor |
| **Spectrum Display** | Title, Y-axis label, grid, peak labels, wavenumber annotations |
| **Update** | Manually re-render the spectrum |

### Canvas Area

- **Combined mode** — all active (visible) functional groups rendered as a single composite IR spectrum
- **Separate mode** — each group displayed as its own stacked trace, color-matched to its sidebar card
- Info bar shows active group count, visible peak count, and wavenumber range

---

## 🧪 Functional Group Database

Groups are organized into chemical classes:

| Class | Examples |
|---|---|
| **Oxygen** | O–H (free, alcohol, phenol, acid), C–O (alcohol, ether, ester, epoxide), C=O (acid, ketone, aldehyde, ester, anhydride, acyl chloride) |
| **Nitrogen** | N–H (primary/secondary amine, amide), C≡N (nitrile), N=O (nitro) |
| **Carbon** | C–H (sp³, sp², sp), C=C (alkene), C≡C (alkyne) |
| **Aromatics** | Mono-, ortho-, meta-, para-disubstituted; Ar C=C ring stretches |
| **Alkenes** | Terminal (=CH₂), trans-, cis- |
| **Halogens** | C–F, C–Cl, C–Br |
| **Sulfur** | S=O (sulfoxide, sulfone, sulfonyl), C–S (thioether), S–H (thiol) |
| **Phosphorus** | P=O, P–O–C, P–OH |
| **Silicon** | Si–H, Si–O–C |

Each entry includes:
- Absorption wavenumber(s) in cm⁻¹
- Relative intensity
- Band label and vibration type (stretch, bend, oop bend, etc.)

---

## 📐 Technical Details

- **Rendering** — HTML5 Canvas 2D API; Gaussian peak model with configurable σ (width factor)
- **Spectrum range** — 4000–1000 cm⁻¹ (transmittance mode)
- **Broad peaks** — O–H, N–H, and acid bands use widened Gaussian profiles automatically
- **Peak shift** — per-band ±200 cm⁻¹ offset, applied at render time
- **Fonts** — IBM Plex Mono + IBM Plex Sans (loaded from Google Fonts)
- **Canvas resolution** — 1100 × 560 px (PNG export at native canvas resolution)
- **CSV format** — `Wavenumber_cm-1;Transmittance_%` (semicolon delimiter, two decimal places)

---

## 📦 File Structure

```
Virtual_IR.html       # Single self-contained file
                      # Includes: CSS, HTML layout, IR database (JS), 
                      #           rendering engine, export functions
```

---

## 🎓 Use Cases

- **Organic chemistry education** — visualize and compare characteristic absorptions of functional groups
- **Spectral interpretation practice** — build a spectrum from known groups and challenge students to identify them
- **Lecture and presentation aid** — export publication-ready PNG spectra
- **Quick reference** — use the built-in absorption table as a concise IR correlation chart
- **Lab report supplement** — export CSV data for plotting in external software

---

## 📤 Exporting

### PNG
Click **↓ PNG** in the header. Saves `IR_Spectrum.png` at full canvas resolution (1100 × 560 px).

### CSV
Click **↓ CSV** in the header. Saves `IR_Spectrum.csv` with columns:

```
Wavenumber_cm-1;Transmittance_%
4000.0;99.87
3999.0;99.91
...
```

Compatible with Excel, Origin, Python (pandas/matplotlib), and R.

---

## 🛠️ Customization

To add new functional groups, extend the `IR_DB` array in the `<script>` section:

```javascript
{
  id: 'my_group',
  name: 'My Bond Name',
  shortName: 'Short Label',
  color: '#hex',
  peaks: [
    { wn: 1750, intensity: 0.95, label: 'My stretch', type: 'stretch' },
  ]
}
```

Peak `type` strings control band width:
- `'stretch'` — default width
- `'stretch, broad'` — broad Gaussian (σ × 4)
- `'stretch, very broad'` — very broad Gaussian (σ × 6)

